{{orphan|date=February 2009}}

'''Geogony''' (or Geogeny) is an antiquated term used to refer to the, at the time, speculative science of the [[Earth]]'s formation and history. The term was used in ''Elementary Geology'' an early [[geology]] book by [[Edward Hitchcock]], eighth edition published in [[New York City]] by Mark H. Newman and Company in 1847.

[[Category:History of Earth science]]


{{geology-stub}}

Hypernuclear spectroscopy is the [[spectroscopy]] or measuring the energy spectra of a [[Hypernucleus]], i.e. an atomic nucleus which has a [[hyperon]] or a [[strange quark]] embedded in it. This is an important field of nuclear physics which helps understand the structure of nuclei and their interactions.

* {{cite journal | url = http://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/1742-6596/299/1/012013/pdf | doi=10.1088/1742-6596/299/1/012013 | volume=299 | title=Hypernuclear Spectroscopy | journal=Journal of Physics: Conference Series | pages=012013}}
* https://arxiv.org/abs/nucl-ex/0408011
* {{cite journal | url = http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0375947486905506 | doi=10.1016/0375-9474(86)90550-6 | volume=450 | title=Experiments on Σ− hypernuclei with in flight kaons | journal=Nuclear Physics A | pages=157–164| bibcode=1986NuPhA.450..157H }}
